{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Siloed-borrowing risk controls are defined but never enforced on borrow","locations":["0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/logic/ValidationLogic.sol:253","0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/configuration/UserConfiguration.sol:196","0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/configuration/ReserveConfiguration.sol:303","0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/helpers/Errors.sol:84"],"claim":"The protocol includes silo-borrowing state helpers (`getSiloedBorrowingState`, `getSiloedBorrowing`) and an explicit `SILOED_BORROWING_VIOLATION` error, but `BorrowLogic.executeBorrow()` delegates to `ValidationLogic.validateBorrow()` and that validation never checks either the requested reserve's silo flag or the user's existing siloed-borrowing state. As a result, borrowing a siloed reserve does not prevent additional borrows, and existing borrows do not prevent borrowing a siloed reserve.","impact":"If governance lists any reserve expecting isolated exposure, borrowers can still combine it with other debts. That defeats the intended risk model for siloed assets and can convert isolated risk into cross-reserve bad debt and insolvency during adverse price moves.","paths":["borrow() -> BorrowLogic.executeBorrow() -> ValidationLogic.validateBorrow()"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"ERC721 liquidation can seize NFT collateral using any listed ERC20 without repaying or even bounding against actual debt","locations":["0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/logic/LiquidationLogic.sol:337","0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/logic/LiquidationLogic.sol:344","0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/logic/LiquidationLogic.sol:389","0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/logic/LiquidationLogic.sol:564","0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/logic/LiquidationLogic.sol:755","0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/logic/ValidationLogic.sol:677","0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/logic/ValidationLogic.sol:695"],"claim":"`executeLiquidateERC721()` computes `actualLiquidationAmount` solely from the NFT price and the caller-chosen `liquidationAsset`. `_calculateERC721LiquidationParameters()` returns the borrower's global debt converted into that asset's units, but `validateLiquidateERC721()` only checks that `globalDebt != 0`; it does not require that the borrower owes the chosen `liquidationAsset`, and it does not cap liquidation by reserve-specific debt or even total debt. After validation, the flow calls `_supplyNewCollateral()` to deposit the chosen ERC20 as fresh collateral for the borrower instead of burning any debt token in that reserve.","impact":"Any undercollateralized NFT-backed account with nonzero debt can have an NFT seized by paying with any listed ERC20 priced by the oracle, even if the borrower never borrowed that asset and even if the amount paid exceeds the borrower's real debt. If a listed ERC20 has a weak or manipulable oracle, an attacker can cheaply seize valuable NFTs while leaving the original debt outstanding, directly harming users and worsening protocol insolvency.","paths":["liquidateERC721(collateralAsset, liquidationAsset=X) -> _calculateERC721LiquidationParameters() -> validateLiquidateERC721() -> _supplyNewCollateral()"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"supplyERC721FromNToken is bricked by `ownerOf` on nonexistent nToken ids","locations":["0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/logic/ValidationLogic.sol:118","0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/logic/ValidationLogic.sol:139","0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/protocol/libraries/logic/SupplyLogic.sol:267","0xaef900f14710d067ae96555486232c7189784f50/contracts/dependencies/openzeppelin/contracts/ERC721.sol:76"],"claim":"Before `executeSupplyERC721FromNToken()` remints the nToken position, `validateSupplyFromNToken()` requires `IERC721(reserveCache.xTokenAddress).ownerOf(tokenId) == address(0)`. Standard OpenZeppelin ERC721 `ownerOf` reverts for nonexistent tokens rather than returning the zero address, so the validation itself reverts precisely in the normal case where the nToken for that tokenId has not been minted yet.","impact":"The `supplyERC721FromNToken` path is effectively unusable, causing a protocol-level denial of service for any recovery, migration, or atomic re-collateralization flow that depends on re-supplying NFTs already held by the NToken contract without a fresh underlying transfer.","paths":["supplyERC721FromNToken() -> SupplyLogic.executeSupplyERC721FromNToken() -> ValidationLogic.validateSupplyFromNToken()"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Incorrect debt calculation uses balanceOf instead of scaledBalanceOf","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Not supported. `IVariableDebtToken` explicitly exposes `balanceOf(user)` as the current debt view, and this helper is used where current debt is needed. The separate `scaledBalanceOf` path in `GenericLogic` is an optimization, not evidence that `balanceOf` is wrong here."},{"title":"Integer overflow in GenericLogic liquidity threshold calculation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Not reportable. The cited multiplications are executed under Solidity 0.8 checked arithmetic, so overflow reverts instead of silently corrupting health factor calculations."},{"title":"Division by zero when liquidation bonus is zero","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Only arises from administrator misconfiguration of reserve parameters. The code does not show an attacker-triggerable path, so this is not a protocol vulnerability."},{"title":"Reentrancy vulnerability in FlashClaimLogic","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Insufficiently supported. The report does not identify a concrete state-corruption path, and the repository snapshot does not expose a vulnerable public `flashClaim` entrypoint that would make the callback reentrancy claim reportable on its own."},{"title":"Reentrancy in marketplace flash loan pattern","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Not supported. The public marketplace entrypoints in `PoolMarketplace` are protected by `nonReentrant`, so a generic callback/reentrancy claim against `_buyWithCredit` is not enough."},{"title":"NFT transferred before state update in supply","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Not reportable. If `executeSupplyERC721Base` reverts, the prior `safeTransferFrom` is reverted as part of the same transaction, so the NFT is not permanently stranded by this ordering alone."},{"title":"Unchecked return value in MarketplaceLogic","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Incorrect. `Address.functionDelegateCall` reverts on failure; the delegatecall result is not silently ignored."},{"title":"Repay with pTokens allows repaying more than debt","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Incorrect. `paybackAmount` is initialized to actual debt and only reduced when `params.amount` is smaller, so repayment is capped at `min(requestedAmount, variableDebt)`."},{"title":"Missing initialization check in ParaProxy constructor","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Deployment self-misconfiguration only. Passing `address(0)` as owner does not create an attacker-triggerable protocol issue."},{"title":"Potential division by zero in GenericLogic","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Not supported. The cited divisions are guarded by explicit nonzero checks on the relevant collateral totals, and the ERC